<li id="cite_note-131"><b><a href="#cite_ref-131" title="">^</a></b> "The <b>Exchange Variation</b> was a feared weapon in the hands of Bobby Fischer". <a href="/wiki/Gary_Kasparov" title="Gary Kasparov" class="mw-redirect">Gary Kasparov</a> and <a href="/wiki/Raymond_Keene" title="Raymond Keene">Raymond Keene</a>, <i>Batsford Chess Openings 2</i>, Collier Books, p. 382. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0020339917" class="internal">ISBN 0-02-033991-7</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-132"><b><a href="#cite_ref-132" title="">^</a></b> "The modern version of the Spanish Exchange variation, which runs 5.0-0 after the exchange on move 4, should be named after former World Champion Bobby Fischer." Fischer, after finding an improvement on a 1965 game Barengdt-Teschner, which Black won brilliantly, "started to play the Exchange with 5.0-0, winning game after game with it, and continued to play it with success even in his 1992 rematch with Boris Spassky, his final formal chess event". <a href="/wiki/Larry_Kaufman" title="Larry Kaufman">Larry Kaufman</a>, <i>The Chess Advantage in Black and White</i>, David McKay, 2004, pp. 4-5. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0812935713" class="internal">ISBN 0-8129-3571-3</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-133"><b><a href="#cite_ref-133" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?yearcomp=exactly&amp;year=&amp;playercomp=white&amp;pid=19233&amp;player=&amp;pid2=&amp;player2=&amp;movescomp=exactly&amp;moves=&amp;opening=&amp;eco=C68-69&amp;result=" class="external text" title="http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?yearcomp=exactly&amp;year=&amp;playercomp=white&amp;pid=19233&amp;player=&amp;pid2=&amp;player2=&amp;movescomp=exactly&amp;moves=&amp;opening=&amp;eco=C68-69&amp;result=" rel="nofollow">Fischer games with Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation</a>. ChessGames.com. Retrieved on 2009-02-19.</li>
<li id="cite_note-134"><b><a href="#cite_ref-134" title="">^</a></b> Carsten Hansen, <i>The Nimzo-Indian: 4 e3</i>. Gambit Publications, 2002. p. 132.</li>
<li id="cite_note-135"><b><a href="#cite_ref-135" title="">^</a></b> Leon Pliester, <i>Rubinstein Complex of the Nimzo-Indian Defense</i>. International Chess Enterprises, 1995. p. 272.</li>
<li id="cite_note-136"><b><a href="#cite_ref-136" title="">^</a></b> Svetozar Gligoric, <i>Play the Nimzo-Indian Defense</i>. Pergamon Press, 1985. p. 65.</li>
<li id="cite_note-137"><b><a href="#cite_ref-137" title="">^</a></b> Watson observed that 7...Qb6 "is an astonishing move that those raised with classical chess principles would simply reject as a typical beginner's mistake. Black goes running after a pawn when he is undeveloped and already under attack." <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREF.5B.5BJohn_L._Watson.7CWatson.2C_John.5D.5D2006"><a href="/wiki/John_L._Watson" title="John L. Watson">Watson, John</a> (2006). <i>Mastering the Chess Openings, Volume 1</i>. Gambit Publications. p.&#160;199. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781904600602" class="internal">ISBN 978-1-904600-60-2</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mastering+the+Chess+Openings%2C+Volume+1&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BJohn+L.+Watson%7CWatson%2C+John%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BJohn+L.+Watson%7CWatson%2C+John%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B199&amp;rft.pub=Gambit+Publications&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-904600-60-2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Bobby_Fischer"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-138"><b><a href="#cite_ref-138" title="">^</a></b> "Referring to the Poisoned Pawn Variation ... the brilliant, classically-oriented grandmaster <a href="/wiki/Salo_Flohr" title="Salo Flohr">Salo Flohr</a> commented, even as late as 1972: 'In chess, there is an old rule: in the opening, one must make haste to develop the pieces, and must not move the same piece several times, particularly the queen. This ancient law holds good even for Bobby Fischer'." <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREF.5B.5BJohn_L._Watson.7CWatson.2C_John.5D.5D1998"><a href="/wiki/John_L._Watson" title="John L. Watson">Watson, John</a> (1998). <i>Secrets of Modern Chess Strategy: Advances since Nimzowitsch</i>. Gambit Publications. p.&#160;18. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1901983072" class="internal">ISBN 1-901983-07-2</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Secrets+of+Modern+Chess+Strategy%3A+Advances+since+Nimzowitsch&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BJohn+L.+Watson%7CWatson%2C+John%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BJohn+L.+Watson%7CWatson%2C+John%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B18&amp;rft.pub=Gambit+Publications&amp;rft.isbn=1-901983-07-2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Bobby_Fischer"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-139"><b><a href="#cite_ref-139" title="">^</a></b> The Poisoned Pawn Variation "was considered dubious by certain GMs and crazy by <a href="/wiki/Bent_Larsen" title="Bent Larsen">Bent Larsen</a>". <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREF.5B.5BLev_Polugaevsky.7CPolugaevsky.2C_L..5D.5D.2C_.5B.5BJeroen_Piket.7CPiket.2C_J..5D.5D.2C_and_Christophe_Gu.C3.A9neau1995"><a href="/wiki/Lev_Polugaevsky" title="Lev Polugaevsky">Polugaevsky, L.</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jeroen_Piket" title="Jeroen Piket">Piket, J.</a>, and Christophe Guéneau (1995). <i>Sicilian Love: Lev Polugaevsky Chess Tournament, Buenos Aires 1994</i>. New in Chess. p.&#160;83. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9071689999" class="internal">ISBN 90-71689-99-9</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Sicilian+Love%3A+Lev+Polugaevsky+Chess+Tournament%2C+Buenos+Aires+1994&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BLev+Polugaevsky%7CPolugaevsky%2C+L.%5D%5D%2C+%5B%5BJeroen+Piket%7CPiket%2C+J.%5D%5D%2C+and+Christophe+Gu%C3%A9neau&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BLev+Polugaevsky%7CPolugaevsky%2C+L.%5D%5D%2C+%5B%5BJeroen+Piket%7CPiket%2C+J.%5D%5D%2C+and+Christophe+Gu%C3%A9neau&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B83&amp;rft.pub=New+in+Chess&amp;rft.isbn=90-71689-99-9&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Bobby_Fischer"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-140"><b><a href="#cite_ref-140" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?yearcomp=exactly&amp;year=&amp;playercomp=black&amp;pid=&amp;player=Fischer&amp;pid2=&amp;player2=&amp;movescomp=exactly&amp;moves=&amp;opening=&amp;eco=B97&amp;result=" class="external text" title="http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?yearcomp=exactly&amp;year=&amp;playercomp=black&amp;pid=&amp;player=Fischer&amp;pid2=&amp;player2=&amp;movescomp=exactly&amp;moves=&amp;opening=&amp;eco=B97&amp;result=" rel="nofollow">Fischer (Black) Poisoned Pawn games</a>. ChessGames.com. Retrieved on 03-22-2009.</li>
<li id="cite_note-141"><b><a href="#cite_ref-141" title="">^</a></b> Kiril Georgiev and Atanas Kolev, <i>The Sharpest Sicilian: A Black Repertoire with 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6</i>. Simolini 94 (Sofia, Bulgaria), 2007. p. 6.</li>
